&s;he de$$ed to hear the &s;ervice for the &s;ick.</P>
<P>Peggy could not read; Mrs. Marl was too much
engaged; the whole hou&s;e had ample employment,
and her reque&s;t was una$tainable.</P>
<P>She then begged they would procure her a prayer|book,
that &s;he might try to read her&s;elf; but her eyes,
heavy, aching, and dim, glared upon the p$per, with|out
