her pre&s;ence, cea&s;ed to operate in her ab&s;ence.&mdash;
He was too noble to betray the well meant, though
not well applied warnings of Dr. Marchmont, yet
he acknowledged, that when left to cool reflection,
a thou&s;and palliations aro&s;e for every &s;tep he could
not po&s;itively vindicate: and when, afterwards,
